@NODE Overview "wbprint.guide/overview"

   @{B}Overwiew@{UB}

   wbprint is a small (~5.7k) Workbench utility to print text 
   files on any Workbench printer

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "wbprint.guide/requirements"

   @{B}Requirements@{UB}

   wbprint requires an Amiga with OS2.04 or higher (it is a
   commodity) and a printer.
	
@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "wbprint.guide/installation"


   @{B}Installation@{UB}

   Unpack the lha archive. The fact that you are reading this
   implies that you have already done so. Doubleclick the "Install"
   icon and follow the instructions. The preferred place for
   wbprint is your "WBStartup" drawer, so that wbprint is
   always available on your system, since it is convinient for
   a quick printout of any text file and it does not need much
   ressources.
   
   NOTE: wbprint will work anyway, regardless of its location
   on your system.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "wbprint.guide/usage"


   @{B}Usage@{UB}

   When started from "WBStart" (or by doubleclicking the wbprint
   icon), wbprint places an icon named "Printer" on the Workbench.

   To print a text file, simply drop its icon onto the "Printer"
   icon. The text will be printed according to your current printer
   setup. That's all.
   
   If you doubleclick the "Printer" icon, an "About" requester with 
   copyright information opens. There are three buttons:
   
   o Continue - go on with the program
   
   o Prefs - starts the printer preferences editor to change the
     printer prefs. See "Configuration"
     
   o Quit - quit the program


   @{U}Configuration@{UU}
   
   You can setup your printer by clicking the "Prefs" button in the
   "About" requester. By default, this will try to run the
   Sys:Prefs/Printer program, which on most systems should be the
   standard workbench printer setup utility.
   
   If, however, your Printer preferences program is located in
   another directory or you use a special printer driver, such as
   TurboPrint (tm), Studio (tm) or the printer drivers from the
   Canon Disk, you will have to specify the preferences program.
   
   To do so, set the Tooltype "PREFS" of the wbprinter program
   to the program (including the full path) you wish to launch.
   
   @{U}Example@{UU}
      
      PREFS=TurboPrint:TurboPrefs
      
   This will (hopefully) invoke the TurboPrint preferences program.
   
   NOTE: It is perfectly OK to specify "PREFS=SYS:tools/calulator",
   in which case the WB calculator program gets called - wbprint
   will not complain. But that is not what the "Prefs" button
   was designed for ;-)

   @{U}The AppIcon@{UU}
  
   Since version 1.1 of wbprint you can customize the location of
   the AppIcon. Simply set the Tooltypes "XPOS" and "YPOS" to the
   desired coordinates. Thanks to Fredrik Söderberg for the suggestion.

   @{U}Example@{UU}

      XPOS=600
      YPOS=380

   This will place the AppIcon in the lower right corner of a 640×480
	workbench screen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Notes "wbprint.guide/notes"

   @{B}Notes@{UB}

   I wrote this program because I had to print a lot of .doc, .txt,
   .asc and other plain ASCII files and the only solution so far
   I found was "type file.txt >PRT:", the "Printfiles" program from
   the tools drawer or loading the file into GoldEd and printing.

   Since I am a rather lazy guy and all of the above involved much
   to much work for a simple job, I created this application that
   does this particular job quick, good (hope so!) and easy.

   @{U}Some Remarks@{UU}

   wbprint is not a printer spooler. If you drop an icon on the
   "Printer" icon, it will get printed (unless you have turned off your
   printer, of course), and you have no way to control that particular
   printout (unless you turn off your printer, of course).

   You can, to avoid accidental printing, deactivate wbprint from
   the "Commodities Exchange" or any compatible replacement. Nothing
   gets printed while wbprint is deactivted. To activate it again,
   select "Enable" from the Commodities Exchange"
   
   wbprint can print ASCII (or ANSI) texts only. If you drop a binary file 
   on it (pictures, sounds etc), it will print garbage! You have been
   warned ;).
   
   Besides these built-in features, I don't know of any bugs, enforcer
   hits or whatever. If you encounter one, send a bug-report to my 
   @{" email address " LINK Author}.
   
@ENDNODE

